---

Why SCD Type 2 Exists
Problem with Type 1:
Old data gets overwritten.
History lost.
But businesses often need:
historical reporting
audit tracking
customer journey analysis
compliance
So instead of overwriting:

> SCD Type 2 creates a NEW row for every change.

---

Core Theory

Definition
SCD Type 2 preserves full historical data by inserting a new row whenever a dimension attribute changes.
Old row remains stored.
---

Real Example
At Amazon
Customer Ravi initially lives in Mumbai.
---

Before Change
customer_key	customer_id	name	city
1	C101	Ravi	Mumbai
---

Later Ravi Moves to Bangalore
Instead of updating row:
NEW row inserted.
---

After Change
customer_key	customer_id	name	city

1	C101	Ravi	Mumbai
2	C101	Ravi	Bangalore

History preserved.


---

Important Insight ⭐

Notice:
customer_id same
BUT:
customer_key changed

This is why surrogate keys are critical in warehouses.
---

Why Surrogate Key Needed

If customer_id itself was primary key:

Cannot store multiple history rows.

Surrogate key solves this.


---

Standard SCD Type 2 Columns ⭐

Usually warehouses add:
Column	Purpose
effective_date	when row became active
end_date	when row expired
is_current	active/inactive flag

---
Real Warehouse Version

customer_key	customer_id	city	effective_date	end_date	is_current

1	C101	Mumbai	2024-01-01	2025-01-10	N
2	C101	Bangalore	2025-01-11	NULL	Y
---

Meaning
Row 1

Mumbai was valid until Jan 10.

Row 2

Bangalore is current active value.
---

Major Advantage ⭐
Now warehouse can answer:
> “Where did Ravi live during 2024 sales?”
Correct historical reporting possible.
---

Example — Historical Analytics
Suppose order placed in 2024.
Fact table linked to:
customer_key = 1

So report still correctly shows Mumbai.
This is why Type 2 is powerful.


---

How ETL Works in Type 2
When change detected:
Step 1
Old row updated:
is_current = 'N'
end_date = yesterday
---

Step 2
New row inserted:

new surrogate key
new values
is_current = 'Y'
---

SQL-Style Thinking
Expire Old Row

UPDATE dim_customer
SET end_date = CURRENT_DATE,
    is_current = 'N'
WHERE customer_id = 'C101'
AND is_current = 'Y';
---

Insert New Row
INSERT INTO dim_customer
VALUES (
   2,
   'C101',
   'Ravi',
   'Bangalore',
   CURRENT_DATE,
   NULL,
   'Y'
);


